result.execSummary:
The defendant Naser A Yusuf was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Naser A Yusuf is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Naser A Yusuf was found guilty of Child Enticement-Sexual Contact, a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.07(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Attorney Jason Zapf appeared for the State. DE appears in person with Atty Terry Rose.   Clerk P. Scypta.   
MINUTES:  843 - Jury not present. Atty Rose requests DE's wife be allowed to remain in the courtroom, as she is no longer intended to be called as a witness by either side - Granted. ST also no longer intends to introduce statements given during the DE's interview. Minor alterations made to jury instructions. 

DAY 2: State's case resumes with testimony. Witnesses sworn and testified: KPD Det. Jeremy DeWitt. State rests. Exhibit #S5 offered & rec'd by the court. Motion held outside the presence of the jury. Atty Rose moves to dismiss case. Arguments heard. For reasons set forth on the record, the Court denies the DE's motion. Jury returns. Defense's case presented. Witnesses sworn and testified: Vontrell C.. Exhibit #D1 offered & rec'd by the court. Motions held outside the presence of the jury. Atty Rose again moves to dismiss - Denied. Atty Rose objects to language in pattern jury instruction. Request to modify language denied. Court reviews all remaining jury/verdict instructions. Jury brought in. Closing arguments heard. Jurors instructed on principals of law. Alternate juror excused at 12:01pm. Bailiffs sworn. Jurors begin deliberations at 1203. Jury reaches verdict at 138. Verdict: guilty on Ct1. Jury polled. Jury released at 1:40pm. ST moves for judgment on the verdict. DE opposes and requests verdict be set aside - Denied. Judgment is granted - DE found guilty by the Court. PSI ordered. ST moves to revoke bond. DE opposes. Discussion held. Court denies bond revocation. ST also moves to amend the bond conditions to prohibit contact with Quality Food Store when it is open to the public - So Ordered.  DE is further ordered to surrender his passport by 5pm to the Clerk of Court. Passport may be returned to the DE on the date of sentencing.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for June 8, 2016 at 09:00 am. Attorney Jason Zapf appeared for the State with KPD Det. Jeremy DeWitt. DE appears in person with Atty Terry Rose and Asst. Tamara Weathersby.   Clerk P. Scypta.   
MINUTES:  853 - Misc. issues reviewed out of the presence of the jury. Atty Rose objects to video proposed for use by the ST. Discussion held. Court takes objection under advisement and makes no ruling at this time. Witnesses sequestered as stipulated by all parties.

DAY 1:  Impaneled jury sworn and pre-instructions given. Opening statements. Jury transported to Quality Foods at 9:45am for view of scene. Jury returns at 10:17am - jury kept in sequestration for court to make a record on the view. Parties agree view was held as stipulated. State presents case. Witnesses sworn and testified: N.M., Genevieve M., Maria V., Juan C., KPD Officer A. Sanderson, KPD Officer J. Niebuhr, KPD Officer S. Morton, KPD Det. J. DeWitt. Exhibits 1-4 marked; #3 offered and rec'd by the court. Jurors released at 4:30pm (with instruction to return at 8:45am on 4/13), as legal arguments must be heard before testimony may continue. Issues heard out of jury's presence re: Miranda Goodchild, coercion. KPD Officer J. DeWitt under oath and testified. Court finds the DE was not in custody during the interview in which statements were made. Any statements made up to the point of the DE being taken into custody is admissible. Court further finds the DE's statements were not coerced in any way. Trial to resume 4/12.  Jury trial scheduled for April 13, 2016 at 09:00 am.
